<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920107-0119</DOCNO><DOCID>920107-0119.</DOCID><HL>   Carolina Power's NRC Fine</HL><DATE>01/07/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CPL</CO><MS>UTILITIES (UTI)</MS><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)NUCLEAR POWER, FUEL (NUK)SOUTHERN U.S. ELECTRIC UTILITIES (UES)</IN><NS>NUCLEAR POWER, ENERGY (NUK)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>GEORGIA (GA)NORTH CAROLINA (NC)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   RALEIGH, N.C. -- Carolina Power andamp; Light Co. said it willnot contest a $125,000 civil penalty proposed by the NuclearRegulatory Commission for alleged violations of NRC rules atthe utility's Brunswick, N.C., nuclear power plant.   Officials in the NRC's Region II office in Atlanta saidthe fine stemmed from two instances in which the company wasfound not to have taken adequate corrective action forprevious violations involving work control and verificationprocedures.</LP><TEXT>   Carolina Power paid an $87,500 fine relating to similarproblems found by the NRC in May 1991.</TEXT></DOC>